                                Report abuseTranscript of The Rooney FamilyThe Rooney Family Art "The Cheif"Rooney Kathleen McNulty Dan Rooney Margaret"Maggie" Murray Daniel M. Rooney 1901-1988 1904-1982 Chairman of the Pittsburgh Steelers franchiseThe US ambassador of Ireland 1932- now Arthur J,Jr. Arthur J. IIIPresident and co-owner of the Pittsburgh Steelers 1935-Now Timothy 1937-now President of Yonkers Raceway at Empire City Patrick 1939-now CEO of Palm Beach Kennel CLub John 1939-now Art Rooney Sr.(left) with his sons Art Rooney Jr.(center) and Dan Rooney when the Steelers won  their third Super Bowl in 1979 . John was Patrick's twin A picture of Art Rooney with twins Patrick and John in 1939 Eloped in New York City onJune 11, 1931 KidsArthurPatriciaKathleen* RitaDaniel Marry DuffyJohnJames Joan KidsArthur J.IIIKaren MichaelSusan Taking Root in America Rooney Family Tree KidsKathleenMargaret Bridget TimothyCara KidsPatrick JoesphTheresaChristopherThomasBrianMonica KidsSeanMaryJoAnnAliceJames*PeterMatthen *Deceased *Deceased Arthur Rooney Catherine Reagen September 1874 Arthur and Catherine made the journey across the ocean in the 1870'sThey originally lived in Youngstown, Ohio before moving to Pittsburgh in 1884 Starting their lives in America Tradgey Strikes Catherine cecilia was born and she died before her second birthdayAnother baby girl was born and she too was named Catherine Cecilia . She unfortunatly met her sisters fateArthur was born and he too died. The Northside Athlete Arthur James Rooney was born on January 29, 1901He played for Phipps Athletic  Association at age seventeen. He was the youngest player on the team of steelworker.Art and his brother Dan competed for the leader in stats. The Rooney family didn't live in Pittsburgh until 1907 when the city annexed the city of Allegheny. They owned  a pub and bording house. It was difficult for them to make money during the prohbiton.The part that was annexed was then called the Northside.The area they lived in was called the ward. Art not only played baseball but football , basketball and boxing.He played a lot of these sports escpecially boxing to help out his paretns during the Prohibition. Sports help a Family in need. When Art was a freshmn at Dusquense he played football on the JV team. "Dusquense Monthly"- " Halfback Rooney stands head and shoulders above his companions" Art excels at Football Art is the fifth from the left in the middle row. Art's Childhood Hero Art looked up to an African American Baseball player by the name of Cumberland Posey. He even played with him on a baseball team which was very odd for the time. Rooney and the NFL Trying to get a Team One huge problem that stood in Art's way was the Blue Laws. The Blue laws prohibited any commerical entertainment which was the only day avaliable for Pro Football Someone on the Enemy Lines Art's brother Jim was a state senator. Jim was trying to get the Blue Laws modified in order to have football on sundays.They almost had a done deal when Jim got into a horrible crash and was in a coma for a few days. The NFL takes root Summer 1933-NFL owner convention at the Fort Pitt Hotel :They welcomed 3 new members.The new members were Art Rooeny from the Pittsburgh Pirates, Bert Bell from the Philidelphia Eagles and the new Cardinals owner Charles Bidwell. Contributions to the NFL The orignal owners They divided the leauge in to two five-team divisions. The winners would meet in a championship game.They allowed passing from anywhere behind the line of scrimmage.The goal posts were moved foward  to make kicking field goals easier.They also changed the football shape to make it easier to throw Starting a Franchise from Nothing Art had a lot of problems finding a stadium.University of Pittsburgh refused to let them use their stadium. Until The owner of the Pittbsburgh Pirates let him use Forbes Field in the fall of 1933. The First Season: A vision of what is to come Uniforms and Logos Their season one record was 3-6-2(w-l-t) Within their next ten years they finall make it to the playoffs in 1947They were horrible In the Beginning In their first ten years they lost or tied 99 of 124 games. After going to the Playoffs in 1947 they did not go to the Playoffs for another 25 years. The Draft Art Rooney and Bert Bell were tired of betting wars over college prospects.1935 leauge meeting- Rooney and Bell decided to bring up tht issue- afterward all of the owners initited the Draft. The War and Combinations Wars  caused a lot of teams to combine 1943 season(World War ii) - The Steelers temporaily combined with the Eagles to become the Steagles1944 season(World War ii)- The Steelers temporaily combined with the Chicago Cardinals to become Card-Pitt Changing names 1933 to 1939-Art's team was called the Pittsburgh Pirates 1940- The Pittsburgh Pirates became the Pittsburgh Steelers to better fit the nickname of Pittsburgh(Steel City) and re-create the team.The name change didn't affect the way the team played. The Same Old Steelers The players they drafted were begging to be traded.Joe Greene's first season as a steeler was 1-13.He even threatened to leave football. Rooney's Place of Refuge Shamrock Farms- A small farm in Virgina was Art Rooney's refuge from football and the city. Football -Not his only venture Rooney-McGinely boxing club was a huge part of  Art's life. If the NFL team didn't work- this was his fallback. The Rooney Twins Kidnapped? August 13, 1952- The Cheif got a ransom note saying that he had to leave $10,000 under a park bench if he valued his twin sons life.September 1952- he got a more ominous note and he follwed the instructions- The FBI watched the bench and it ended up being young teenage girls Impact on Civil Rights He fired a coach (Bill Austin)- Austin had some issues but a main issue was his problem with African Americans.Construction of Three Rivers Stadium- Art made sure that there were African American union workers bulding it. A Decade of Change In order of apperence Jack Lambert, Mean Joe Greene, Art "The Cheif" Rooney and Terry Bradshaw The 70's brought a new faith to the Pittsburgh Steelers and Art Rooney.1970 and 1971-the only years in the 70's that the Steelers did not make a playoff appearence. 1972 New Recruits 1969- "Mean"Joe Greene(DT)- first round 1970-Terry Bradshaw(QB)- 1st round1971- Jack Ham(LB)-2nd Round1972-Franco Harris(RB)-1st round1974-Jack Lambert(LB)- 2nd round THE STEEL CURTAIN #75 "Mean" Joe Greene - defensive tackle, 1969-1981 #68 L. C. Greenwood - defensive end, 1969-1981 #63 Ernie Holmes - defensive tackle, 1972–1977#78 Dwight White - defensive end, 1971–1980#47 Mel Blount- Cornerback, 1970-1983#58 Jack Lambert- Linebacker 1974-1984#59 Jack Ham- Linebacker 1971-1982 They won this game but lose in the next game against the Miami Dolphins FRANCO HARRIS The Best Coach Yet Chuck Noll:1969-1991 Coached the team for 22 seasonsWon 4 Superbowls11 Playoff ApperencesHe was also the first coach to coach the Steeler for more than 2 years Super Bowl Legacy Starts 1/12/1975-Pitt 16-MN 6- MVP Franco Harris  1/18/1976-Pitt 21-Dallas 17- MVP Lynn Swann1/21/1979-Pitt 35-Dallas 31 - MVP Terry Bradshaw1/20/1980-Pitt 31-Los Angeles Rams 19- MVP Terry Bradshaw Their Own Words about The Cheif The Merger 1970 the Steelers in order to complete a merger with the AFL went to the AFC. This was the Offical merger.The start of the Super Bowl was the unoffical merger in 1967. A Sad Day for Steeler Nation grandfather of United States Congressman Thomas J. Rooneygreat-grandfather of actresses Kate Mara and Rooney Mara. Family Ties Kate Mara- notable roles: Brokeback Mountain(charater was the daughter of Heath Ledger) and the TV show 24 Rooney Mara- Social Network and The Girl with the Dragon Tatoo August 25,1988- Art Rooney died at Mercy Hospital, Pittsburgh- 87 years old He suffered a stroke the day before in his office at Three Rivers Stadium.He died in his sleep surrounded by his family. The Cheif's Dream Lives 2 More Super Bowls A New Stadium Fans rated the best in the Leauge Terrible Towels Still Flying! Former Vice President of the Pittsburgh SteelersCo-owner of the Pittsburgh SteelersFormer Scout for the SteelersFull transcriptMore presentations by
    
        
